<S ID="4">WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</S>
<S ID="5">WU LABOR</S>
<S ID="6">Western Union Corp. said <COREF ID="X1">its subsidiary, </COREF>Western Union Telegraph Co., agreed to extend <COREF ID="X2">labor contracts</COREF> with <COREF ID="X3">the United Telegraph Workers and the Communications Workers of America</COREF> for three years.</S>
<S ID="7">The contracts, signed in 1985 following strikes by the unions, were to expire Aug. 6, according to the Upper Saddle River, N.J.-based communications systems company.</S>
<S ID="8"><COREF ID="X4">The agreement</COREF> provides for a one-year extension of the existing contracts.</S>
<S ID="9">At the end of the first and second years, the company or the unions may choose to renegotiate wages, pensions and health care.</S>
<S ID="10">The accord also provides for cost-of-living adjustments in the second and third years.</S>
<S ID="11">The United Telegraph Workers union represents 4,400 Western Union employees around the country.</S>
<S ID="12">The Communications Workers of America represents 300 company employees in New York City.</S>